characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Grzegorz, Irena, Lucyna, Witold.","Polish (mainly <b>Łada</b>) and Czech (Moravian): from a short form of the Polish personal name <i>Ładysław</i>, Czech <i>Ladislav</i>, both from <i>Vladislav</i> (Latinized as <i>Ladislaus</i>), a Slavic name composed of the elements <i>vlad</i> ‘to rule’ (from Old Slavic <i>vlasti</i>, later <i>vladati</i>) + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’ (from <i>slava</i> ‘glory’). Compare 2 below.","Hungarian: from <i>Lad(a)</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Ladomér</i>, a Hungarian form of Slavic <i>Vladimir</i> (see   Lado   2, compare 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Isolda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The name of the tragic mistress of Tristan in the Arthurian romances. There are several versions of the story. The main features are that the beautiful Isolde, an Irish princess, is betrothed to the aged King Mark of Cornwall. However, through accidentally drinking a magic potion, she and the young Cornish knight Tristan fall in love, with tragic consequences. The story has exercised a powerful hold on the European imagination. The name was relatively common in Britain in the Middle Ages, but is much rarer today."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Isolda Lapy was born about 1272, in Denton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She married William de Bois I about 1287, in Fersfield, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1350, in Coningsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 80."},"et":{"Abt 1272–about 1350":"umbes 1272–umbes 1350","1270–1311":"1270–1311","1296–1329":"1296–1329","1272–1350":"1272–1350","Abt 1272":"umbes 1272","1311":"1311","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","16 November 1311":"16. november 1311","1296":"1296","1350":"1350","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","about 1350":"umbes 1350","about 1296":"umbes 1296","<, Denton, Norfolk, Eng